Seems that the AspNetCore Signalr Client doesn't respect the cancellationtoken passed into the StartAsync() method.

### Expected Behavior

Connection to hub is terminated when cancellation is requested.

### Steps To Reproduce

Server:

Program.cs
```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddSignalR();

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapHub<MyHub>("/hub");
app.Run();
```

MyHub.cs
```csharp
public class MyHub : Hub
{
    public override Task OnConnectedAsync()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"New connection with id: {Context.ConnectionId} -- {Context.UserIdentifier}");
        return base.OnConnectedAsync();
    }

    public override Task OnDisconnectedAsync(Exception? exception)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Disconnected");
        return base.OnDisconnectedAsync(exception);
    }
}
```

Client:
```csharp
var hubConnection = new HubConnectionBuilder()
    .WithUrl("http://localhost:5151/hub")
    .Build();

Console.WriteLine("Starting connection...");
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await hubConnection.StartAsync(cts.Token);
Console.WriteLine("Connection started.");

await Task.Delay(5000);
Console.WriteLine("Stopping connection...");
await cts.CancelAsync();
Console.WriteLine("Connection stopped.");


while (true)
{
    await Task.Delay(1000);
    Console.WriteLine("Waiting...");
}
```

Disconnect log on server occurs only when you stop the app.

### Workaround
Client:
```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
cts.Token.Register(() => hubConnection.StopAsync());
await hubConnection.StartAsync(cts.Token);
```

